13
00:00:53,086 --> 00:00:55,268
We didn't just have those 16 colors for this game.

14
00:00:55,308 --> 00:00:58,471
The entire industry had those specific 16 colors

15
00:00:58,691 --> 00:00:59,972
to do every game they did.

16
00:01:01,133 --> 00:01:01,473
Those 16 colors.

17
00:01:03,339 --> 00:01:09,243
were arrived at by well-intentioned programmers who simply slid the RGB numbers to even intervals

18
00:01:09,303 --> 00:01:11,884
and said, look how symmetrical, how balanced we're done.

19
00:01:12,745 --> 00:01:16,327
And the rest of us were left to do the crying and the cleanup.

20
00:01:17,308 --> 00:01:23,211
So when I was hired at Lucasfilm, we couldn't even dither these colors because dither didn't

21
00:01:23,251 --> 00:01:24,672
compress in those days.

22
00:01:25,933 --> 00:01:29,195
So I did the best I could to do this.

23
00:01:32,912 --> 00:01:35,773
And then we went on to dither.

24
00:01:36,314 --> 00:01:37,914
I had a little something to do with this.

25
00:01:39,115 --> 00:01:42,096
I put up some pictures on screen one day

26
00:01:42,216 --> 00:01:43,836
after we were done with Zach McCracken

27
00:01:43,876 --> 00:01:45,017
and the alien mind benders,

28
00:01:45,217 --> 00:01:46,978
which those things were just from,

29
00:01:47,858 --> 00:01:50,599
and I said, you know, if we used dither,

30
00:01:52,460 --> 00:01:54,280
our pictures could look like this.

31
00:01:55,981 --> 00:01:57,982
And believe it or not, this was a lot better.

32
00:01:58,582 --> 00:02:00,743
So, inspired by that,

33
00:02:03,647 --> 00:02:07,648
We learned how to compress dither thanks to Ron Gilbert, who is sitting in this room someplace.

34
00:02:08,988 --> 00:02:13,329
And we made a game where you could actually have six or seven different kinds of blue,

35
00:02:14,190 --> 00:02:17,851
rather than just four, because of the fact that we could dither it.

36
00:02:19,191 --> 00:02:23,192
This was all EGA. It was all, as you can see, very low resolution.

37
00:02:26,165 --> 00:02:28,766
This game actually won graphics awards.

38
00:02:28,846 --> 00:02:30,767
Some people actually thought it was a VGA game

39
00:02:30,807 --> 00:02:33,528
because they'd never seen EGA graphics look like this.

40
00:02:36,729 --> 00:02:37,490
When we were done with that,

41
00:02:37,530 --> 00:02:40,391
we went on to make a game called The Secret of Monkey Island,

42
00:02:40,831 --> 00:02:42,492
which some of you have probably heard of.

43
00:02:44,313 --> 00:02:45,473
The Secret of Monkey Island,

44
00:02:45,573 --> 00:02:47,474
we really got the use of Dither Down.

45
00:02:50,976 --> 00:02:52,156
In The Secret of Monkey Island,

46
00:02:53,327 --> 00:02:56,888
We could have places that looked a lot less flat than those Zach McCracken environments.

47
00:02:57,108 --> 00:02:59,548
We could have real sunsets in EGA.

48
00:03:02,569 --> 00:03:04,430
We could have atmospheric perspective.

49
00:03:07,530 --> 00:03:10,591
We could have depth of field still in EGA.

50
00:03:13,791 --> 00:03:16,872
We could render sand so that it looked a little bit like sand

51
00:03:17,332 --> 00:03:20,253
and not like a large yellow spot that someone had forgotten to color in.

52
00:03:23,064 --> 00:03:25,346
It was exciting and inspirational for us artists.

53
00:03:26,927 --> 00:03:28,329
And then we moved on from there.

54
00:03:31,611 --> 00:03:36,015
I'm gonna now just put on a slideshow of other 256 color.

55
00:03:36,035 --> 00:03:43,221
8-bit art I have done.

56
00:03:43,701 --> 00:03:46,804
Everything you're seeing now was done 8-bit.

57
00:03:48,045 --> 00:03:49,446
This is not 8-bit-ish art yet.

58
00:03:49,666 --> 00:03:50,627
I'll get to that in a minute.

59
00:03:51,734 --> 00:03:57,839
