60
00:04:00,501 --> 00:04:01,422
This is what I've been doing.

61
00:04:02,363 --> 00:04:05,446
And while this is showing, I would like to talk a little bit about

62
00:04:06,767 --> 00:04:13,112
the reason I am so, and remained so, interested in 8-bit, 256 color, limited palette art,

63
00:04:13,453 --> 00:04:17,796
even after there was any technological or game design imperative to use it.

64
00:04:19,129 --> 00:04:22,552
I am interested in it because it was so incredibly limited.

65
00:04:23,393 --> 00:04:28,657
I don't actually have any desire to do EGA art ever again in my life, but I will say

66
00:04:28,677 --> 00:04:34,782
that the most creative work I ever did was done when I just had those 16 horrible colors

67
00:04:34,862 --> 00:04:35,383
to do it in.

68
00:04:36,243 --> 00:04:40,845
If somebody gives you two gum wrappers and three sticks and tells you to make the pieta with this,

69
00:04:41,426 --> 00:04:45,507
you will take two gum wrappers and three sticks as far as they can possibly go

70
00:04:45,527 --> 00:04:48,628
in your effort to accomplish your mission.

71
00:04:49,289 --> 00:04:54,591
If somebody gives you all the artistic resources of the universe and says make the pieta with this,

72
00:04:55,311 --> 00:04:59,673
you will dabble in all of those resources until the time is up and you have made nothing at all.

73
00:05:00,692 --> 00:05:04,234
I think this is one of the challenges that's been facing our industry for some time,

74
00:05:04,494 --> 00:05:08,175
is that the resources are so many now, they are so vast,

75
00:05:08,755 --> 00:05:12,957
and they replace themselves and render themselves obsolete so quickly

76
00:05:13,357 --> 00:05:17,898
that nobody has the time to do anything but just dabble for a moment in the current

77
00:05:18,519 --> 00:05:23,040
resource du jour before it's gone, and they are busy scrambling to learn

78
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:25,741
just the merest proficiency of the next one.

79
00:05:26,622 --> 00:05:33,386
Back in these days, I was able to work with Deluxe Paint 2 by Electronic Arts for 10 years

80
00:05:33,967 --> 00:05:37,369
before I had to give that up and go on to the next art tool.

81
00:05:37,749 --> 00:05:42,113
And during that 10 years, I was able to do things with Deluxe Paint that I don't think

82
00:05:42,213 --> 00:05:45,375
even EA ever imagined would be done with Deluxe Paint.

83
00:05:46,175 --> 00:05:47,977
I'm going to get out of this for a moment

84
00:05:49,838 --> 00:05:53,961
and show you some of what I ended up doing with Deluxe Paint.

85
00:05:55,148 --> 00:05:58,129
All of the animation that you see in these scenes right now

86
00:05:59,529 --> 00:06:00,630
is done with ColorCycling.

87
00:06:01,050 --> 00:06:02,150
There are no frames here.

88
00:06:02,890 --> 00:06:04,371
There's no extra pieces of art.

89
00:06:06,432 --> 00:06:10,013
This is actually an HTML5 ColorCycling emulator

90
00:06:10,073 --> 00:06:12,514
created by Joe Huckabee, whom I will

91
00:06:12,534 --> 00:06:13,634
mention a little bit later.

92
00:06:15,395 --> 00:06:17,236
so that anybody could see these pieces.

93
00:06:17,636 --> 00:06:19,136
These were done for software products

94
00:06:19,176 --> 00:06:20,537
that had been dead for ages,

95
00:06:21,357 --> 00:06:25,259
until Joe learned how to show them happening on the web,

96
00:06:25,940 --> 00:06:29,841
and then they became pretty widely seen

97
00:06:29,881 --> 00:06:31,082
and pretty widely liked.

98
00:06:33,263 --> 00:06:35,464
So here are snowflakes falling on a picture.

99
00:06:35,484 --> 00:06:37,525
There is no actual transparency here.

100
00:06:37,605 --> 00:06:39,946
This is one layer of eight-bit art

101
00:06:40,866 --> 00:06:43,988
with apparently transparent snowflakes falling in it.

102
00:06:45,588 --> 00:06:46,789
Here's Waterfall and Rain.

103
00:06:46,809 --> 00:06:55,635
I will be talking just a little bit later about specifically how I did some of these

104
00:06:55,715 --> 00:06:57,276
effects in an 8-bit environment.

105
00:07:00,418 --> 00:07:06,943
Today Deluxe Paint 2 is barely usable even in a DOS emulator, as you will see when I

106
00:07:06,983 --> 00:07:09,905
try to use it in a DOS emulator in just a little while.

107
00:07:11,099 --> 00:07:14,640
The only real tool for producing true 8-bit art

108
00:07:15,040 --> 00:07:16,761
that I know of out there right now

109
00:07:17,021 --> 00:07:20,182
is a program many of you probably know called Promotion.

110
00:07:20,962 --> 00:07:23,503
I am actually very grateful to Cosmigo

111
00:07:23,563 --> 00:07:25,863
for doing all that he has done

112
00:07:26,484 --> 00:07:29,805
to keep an 8-bit tool alive and functioning out there.

113
00:07:30,565 --> 00:07:33,186
But I have to say, there are a number of things

114
00:07:33,246 --> 00:07:39,167
DeepPaint did that Promotion doesn't.

115
00:07:39,367 --> 00:07:40,708
And some of them are pretty important.

116
00:07:41,614 --> 00:07:52,844
Right now, I'm not sure that there are ways to do some of what I did these pictures with in DeepPaint, which is what these were all done in DeepPaint.

117
00:07:54,658 --> 00:08:02,784
However, I will say that Joe Huckabee hopes to have a product ready to look at sometime next year that does all of this again,

118
00:08:03,624 --> 00:08:05,546
and at the higher resolutions you want.

119
00:08:05,986 --> 00:08:12,711
So those of you who are really waiting for a tool you can do stuff like this in 8-bit will probably have it sometime next year.

120
00:08:13,732 --> 00:08:16,714
In the meantime, I'm left to ask myself, as people...

121
00:08:18,572 --> 00:08:23,334
invite me to talk here why we are so interested in 8-bit art when in fact

122
00:08:24,055 --> 00:08:26,716
there's so little way to produce it anymore and

123
00:08:27,596 --> 00:08:28,337
so few really

124
00:08:29,777 --> 00:08:34,139
integrally compelling reasons to be doing 8-bit art in today's

125
00:08:34,660 --> 00:08:38,921
gaming universe and I have pretty much come to the conclusion that

126
00:08:40,562 --> 00:08:43,183
most of you are probably here because you just love this aesthetic

127
00:08:44,327 --> 00:08:49,592
Because maybe some of you remember playing games that looked and felt like this when you were younger

128
00:08:50,233 --> 00:08:56,479
before the very cinemagraphic first-person shooters that we mostly play today came along.

129
00:08:57,485 --> 00:09:02,027
Maybe some of you really love 8-bit because you've never seen anything like this,

130
00:09:02,367 --> 00:09:07,568
being much younger and not have played these games back or used these products back when they were made.

131
00:09:08,128 --> 00:09:13,570
Whatever your reasons, I'm going to assume that you're here for inspiration about thinking about 8-bit art.

132
00:09:13,670 --> 00:09:20,192
And the first thing I want to say along those lines is that for me, 8-bit art is all about

133
00:09:21,432 --> 00:09:24,093
an environment that is small enough to be creative in.

134
00:09:25,046 --> 00:09:28,997
What can you think to do with pixels and with a limited palette?

135
00:09:29,582 --> 00:09:32,363
The great thing about a limited palette is that you can use it.

136
00:09:32,623 --> 00:09:33,604
You can manipulate it.

137
00:09:33,724 --> 00:09:36,406
It isn't just there, a giant ineffable cloud,

138
00:09:36,466 --> 00:09:39,207
like the 32-bit universe that provides

139
00:09:39,507 --> 00:09:40,568
whatever is called for.

140
00:09:40,828 --> 00:09:42,709
You can actually go in and fool around.

141
00:09:43,370 --> 00:09:45,771
What you're seeing over there on the right-hand side

142
00:09:45,811 --> 00:09:49,233
of these things is, your right-hand side, I assume,

143
00:09:49,713 --> 00:09:51,234
is the palette operating.

144
00:09:51,454 --> 00:09:54,316
So you can see what parts are actually cycling

145
00:09:54,356 --> 00:09:55,336
and what parts aren't.

146
00:09:57,516 --> 00:10:00,738
Once I figured out how to do effects like these with color cycling,

147
00:10:04,981 --> 00:10:09,824
I went on to figure out how we could do more with an 8-bit environment.

148
00:10:10,945 --> 00:10:13,186
So here we're going to see some of those same scenes.

149
00:10:22,552 --> 00:10:23,833
So what you're going to see now...

150
00:10:25,864 --> 00:10:27,967
does not involve any extra frames of art either.

151
00:10:28,328 --> 00:10:29,890
Not a single animation frame,

152
00:10:31,313 --> 00:10:32,915
not a single second piece of art.

153
00:10:34,277 --> 00:10:38,243
What you're seeing now is all done simply by changing palettes on this one picture.

154
00:10:41,047 --> 00:10:47,553
Once I figured out how to rotate palette positions to create the sense of animation for almost any environmental effect I could think of,

155
00:10:47,913 --> 00:10:52,797
I started trying to figure out how to make the whole picture change by constructing it,

156
00:10:53,297 --> 00:10:58,982
so that using palettes we could get it at any time of day in virtually any weather condition.

157
00:11:00,363 --> 00:11:04,026
I'm flipping quickly forward to get you some of the more interesting ones.

158
00:11:04,126 --> 00:11:05,567
Actually, that was an interesting one.

