00:11:47,623 --> 00:11:51,425
that I figured out in extremis about seven or eight,

168
00:11:51,505 --> 00:11:53,506
maybe 10 years ago, I can't remember.

169
00:11:58,888 --> 00:12:01,729
So we were doing a game for one of these little

170
00:12:01,749 --> 00:12:03,170
you plug it into your TV,

171
00:12:03,750 --> 00:12:05,430
the game is in the controller things.

172
00:12:05,811 --> 00:12:07,291
It was an X-Men game.

173
00:12:07,771 --> 00:12:09,592
And suddenly, after all these years,

174
00:12:09,892 --> 00:12:12,213
storage and processing time and all the rest of that

175
00:12:12,833 --> 00:12:14,374
really was an issue.

176
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:20,564
So we needed to cram as much art as we could in as little space as possible.

177
00:12:20,644 --> 00:12:25,009
So we had this game, it was a storm game, the character Storm.

178
00:12:25,329 --> 00:12:27,571
She fights people off while flying through the air.

179
00:12:27,671 --> 00:12:28,912
So we needed a lot of backgrounds.

180
00:12:29,152 --> 00:12:31,635
These backgrounds were all designed to scanline parallax.

181
00:12:31,675 --> 00:12:34,517
So they were whizzing by underneath you in a kind of perspective.

182
00:12:34,998 --> 00:12:37,120
And we needed as many of these environments as we could,

183
00:12:37,160 --> 00:12:38,421
but we didn't really have much space.

184
00:12:39,122 --> 00:12:43,184
So here's a valley scene. Imagine storm is flying along up here.

185
00:12:43,664 --> 00:12:46,706
First of all, we wanted these scenes at different times of day.

